Also, Saint Sophia is the name of the Greek Orthodox Cathedral in Los Angeles.

snippet.textDisplay:
1) He's not summoning that red ball, telekinesis is not one of his powers, rather I think that red stuff is the echolocation visualized, I think he bounced a squash/racketball ball of the wall of his glass cage and caught it with his eyes closed.
2) When he's sitting on that body screaming he's in the same hallway as when he's bouncing off the walls destroying art: in the bouncing clip he sends a vase tumbling, and in the grief/rage clip that vase is standing on a table right behind him. So he either kills that person himself and feels guilty and mad at himself about it, or some one else kills that person and he's enraged with desire for revenge, and leaps up off the body upsetting the table and sending the vase flying.
3) I know that in the comics Morbius got his powers from science rather than dark magic, though that really doesn't seem to make sense when he starts flying superman style with no wings, but it almost looks like there is writing on the knife he cuts himself with in front of the bat cave, and the MCU's take on Magic is that it and science are really two sides of the same coin, so I wouldn't rule out magic, or a further blurring of the lines between magic and science, for this adaptation.

2) When he's sitting on that body screaming he's in the same hallway as when he's bouncing off the walls destroying art: in the bouncing clip he sends a vase tumbling, and in the grief/rage clip that vase is standing on a table right behind him.  So he either kills that person himself and feels guilty and mad at himself about it, or some one else kills that person and he's enraged with desire for revenge, and leaps up off the body upsetting the table and sending the vase flying.
3) I know that in the comics Morbius got his powers from science rather than dark magic, though that really doesn't seem to make sense when he starts flying superman style with no wings, but it almost looks like there is writing on the knife he cuts himself with in front of the bat cave, and the MCU's take on Magic is that it and science are really two sides of the same coin, so I wouldn't rule out magic, or a further blurring of the lines between magic and science, for this adaptation.
